<header class="header">
  <h1>Determinate vs Indeterminate Tomatoes</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Understand tomato growth habit before choosing a variety for your season.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Determinate tomatoes tend to concentrate harvests on shorter plants, while indeterminate tomatoes keep growing and producing until frost or disease ends the season.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    Choose determinate tomatoes when you want compact plants, container-friendly growth, or a more concentrated harvest. Choose indeterminate tomatoes when you want an extended harvest and have enough season, space, and support.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Determinate:</strong> shorter plants, concentrated harvest, often easier to manage</li>
    <li><strong>Indeterminate:</strong> longer vines, extended harvest, needs more support</li>
    <li><strong>Short-season fit:</strong> either can work if the variety is early enough</li>
    <li><strong>Main risk:</strong> late indeterminate varieties may set fruit that never ripens before frost</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Determinate Tomatoes Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    Determinate tomatoes are useful when you want a plant that stays more compact and produces much of its crop over a shorter window. This can be helpful for containers, small gardens, and gardeners who want to process a batch of tomatoes at once.
  </p>
  <p>
    In short seasons, determinate tomatoes can be useful because they may focus production before frost. But the variety still needs enough warmth and time to ripen fruit.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Indeterminate Tomatoes Are Best For</h2>
  <p>
    Indeterminate tomatoes keep growing, flowering, and setting fruit as long as conditions allow. They are often a good choice when you want a steady harvest over many weeks.
  </p>
  <p>
    The tradeoff is that they need stronger support and may continue setting late fruit that never ripens in short seasons. Gardeners in cool climates often need to manage them more actively near the end of summer.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Which Type Is Better for Short Seasons?</h2>
  <p>
    Growth habit matters, but maturity timing matters more. An early indeterminate tomato may outperform a late determinate tomato in a short season. A compact determinate tomato may also be useful if you want a concentrated harvest before frost.
  </p>
  <p>
    Instead of choosing by habit alone, compare the full variety: days to maturity, fruit size, harvest pattern, disease tolerance, and how much warm weather your location usually provides.
  </p>
</section>

