<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Comparing Tomato Types</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Assuming determinate always means early:</strong> growth habit and maturity are separate traits.</li>
    <li><strong>Assuming indeterminate always means too late:</strong> some indeterminate varieties are early enough for short seasons.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring support needs:</strong> indeterminate plants can become difficult without staking or cages.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing by habit only:</strong> fruit size and ripening time matter just as much.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting late fruit keep setting:</strong> in short seasons, late flowers may not have time to ripen.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Most Gardens</h2>
  <p>
    Many gardeners do best with a mix: one early tomato for the first harvest, one dependable main-crop tomato, and one variety chosen for flavor or use. In short seasons, make sure at least one variety is early enough to ripen before frost.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more short-season options, see <a href="https://varieties.growbydate.com/tomatoes/short-season-tomato-varieties/">short-season tomato varieties</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Determinate and indeterminate tomatoes can both work when the variety, transplant timing, and frost window fit your location. The best choice depends on how much warm season remains after transplanting.
